- Using the compound angle identity from the formula booklet we can write

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \cos{(A+B)}&=\cos A \cos B - \sin A \sin B\\[6pt]
      \cos{(2\theta+\theta)}&=\cos 2\theta \cos \theta - \sin 2\theta \sin \theta\\[6pt]
      \cos{3\theta}&=\cos 2\theta \cos \theta - \sin 2\theta \sin \theta \tag*{\textbf{M1A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can now the use the double angle formula to rewrite $\cos {2\theta}$ and $\sin {2\theta}$ in terms of single angle functions.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \cos{3\theta}&=(2\cos^2{\theta}-1) \cos \theta - (2\sin{\theta}\cos{\theta}) \sin \theta \tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[6pt]
      &=2\cos^3\theta-\cos \theta - 2\sin^2{\theta}\cos{\theta}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now rewrite $\sin^2{\theta}$ in terms of $\cos{\theta}$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \cos{3\theta}&=2\cos^3\theta-\cos \theta - 2(1-\cos^2{\theta})\cos{\theta}\tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[6pt]
      &=2\cos^3\theta-\cos \theta - 2\cos{\theta}+2\cos^3{\theta}\\[6pt]
      &=\hspace{0.525em}\answer{4\cos^3\theta-3\cos \theta} \hspace{2em}\text{... as required.}
  \end{align*}
  $$

