- $f(x)$ must have a single distinct root and a repeated root to intersect the $x-$axis exactly twice.
  Recall the three roots to $f(x)$ are $\alpha, \beta$ and $\cos k$.
  We have a repeated root when any of these conditions are met.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{white}{hack}\tag*{\textbf{M1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \alpha &= \beta &[1]\\[6pt]
      \alpha &= \cos k &[2]\\[6pt]
      \beta &= \cos k &[3]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Let's consider condition $[1]$ first

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \alpha &= \beta\\[6pt]
      \frac{-\cos k + \sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}&=\frac{-\cos k - \sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}\tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[6pt]
      \frac{\sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}&=-\frac{\sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}\\[6pt]
      \sin k&=0 \hspace{2em} \text{ where $0 \leq k \leq 360^\circ$}\\[6pt]
      k&=0, 180^\circ, 360^\circ \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now consider condition $[2]$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \alpha &= \cos k\\[6pt]
      \frac{-\cos k + \sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}&=\cos k \tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[6pt]
      \frac{-\cos k + \sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}&=\frac{2\cos k}{2}\\[6pt]
      \frac{-3\cos k + \sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}&=0\\[6pt]
      \sqrt{3}\sin k&=3\cos k\\[6pt]
      \tan k&= \sqrt{3}\hspace{2em} \text{ where $0 \leq k \leq 360^\circ$}\\[6pt]
      k&=60^\circ, 240^\circ \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Finally consider condition $[3]$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \beta &= \cos k\\[6pt]
      \frac{-\cos k - \sqrt{3}\sin k}{2}&=\cos k \tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[6pt]
      \tan k&= -\sqrt{3}\hspace{2em} \text{ where $0 \leq k \leq 360^\circ$}\\[6pt]
      k&=120^\circ, 300^\circ \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence $f(x)$ will intersect the $x-$axis exactly $2$ times when

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \tcbhighmath{k=0^\circ, 60^\circ, 120^\circ, 180^\circ, 240^\circ, 300^\circ, 360^\circ}
  \end{align*}
  $$
